gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Anabel</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Ivana</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Marin</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF029934%2F1"><gtr:id>FE8E9269-4CB9-4E60-8A31-68B5C8BD080E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Technologically Active Subsidiaries and FDI-related spillover in industrialising countries: Evidence from Argentina, India, Brazil, and China</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F029934/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This fellowship is about foreign direct investment (FDI) related technology spillovers. Governments in developing (and developed) countries spend large sums to attract multinational companies (MNCs). However, the only welfare justification for subsidising MNCs is that MNC investment ought to generate external spillover effects (spillovers from FDI are all non-market mediated technological benefits generated by an MNC in the host country). Most of the empirical literature has not, however, identified the expected spillovers or explained why they do not appear to occur. The research associated with this fellowship suggests that this is because of a mismatch between the key assumptions underlying the conventional approach to investigating and thinking about spillovers, and those reflected in recent theorising about how MNCs operate. Those conventional approaches assume that spillovers of superior technology follow on almost inevitably from the technology developed by MNCs in their home country. The superior knowledge is delivered from MNCs to subsidiaries, whereupon it ?leaks? to domestic firms without subsidiaries playing any important active role.An alternative model has been proposed in which knowledge spillovers from subsidiaries reflect the active accumulation and creation of knowledge by subsidiaries themselves. Completed empirical analysis of FDI-related spillovers in Argentina suggests the importance of this alternative model. The current fellowship will integrate that analysis&amp;nbsp; with empirical work in three other major industrialising economies: India, Brazil and China. This integration will allow for the control of country-specific characteristics and exploit and explore relevant differences across countries and periods of time.
